title.narrative: 2.3 HEALTH WORKERS, FEMALE COMMUNITY HEALTH VOLUNTEERS AND COMMUNITIES HAVE INCRE

description.narrative: 2.3 Health workers, FCHVs and communities have increased capacity to stimulate demand for supplementation (Vitamin A, IFA, MNP) and to promote fortified foods (iodised salt, wheat flour) and a diversified diet, which contributes to Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being, Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: 2. Nutrition: By 2022, children including adolescent girls and women of reproductive age have improved and equitable access to and use of adequate nutritious diet and improved nutritional care behaviour and care practices.

description.narrative: UNICEF technical assistance and support to the Ministry of Health and Population, contributed to sustained micronutrient intake among children and pregnant and lactating women.
